bob78711new 2025-01-25 03:58 p.m.
@mike_bn @andysofun

Emergency and Verbal motion:

Your Honor, the defense moves to disqualify the replacement video evidence submitted by the prosecution and, in the alternative, requests the dismissal of this case on the following grounds:

1. Spoliation of Evidence
The original video, which was referenced in the affidavit of probable cause and central to this case, has been deleted. The replacement video submitted by the prosecution cannot be verified as identical to the original due to the lack of chain of custody or authentication. Under Arizona v. Youngblood, 488 U.S. 51 ( 1988), the destruction of evidence, particularly when it is material and potentially exculpatory, constitutes a violation of the defendant’s due process rights.

2. Lack of Authentication
Pursuant to Mayfl. R. Ev. 11(1)(a), all evidence must be authenticated to prove its genuineness. The prosecution has failed to authenticate this replacement video. Without the original video, the court cannot determine whether this evidence is accurate, unaltered, or even the same video described in the affidavit of probable cause.

3. Prejudice to the Defendant
The deletion of the original video deprives the defendant of the opportunity to fully challenge the evidence. This creates substantial prejudice against my client, violating his constitutional right to a fair trial under Brady v. Maryland, 373 U.S. 83 (1963).

4. Remedy Requested
We respectfully request that the court disqualify the replacement video from being admitted as evidence. Furthermore, if the video was the sole basis for probable cause in this case, we request that the court dismiss the charges due to the prosecution’s failure to preserve critical evidence.

Thank you, Your Honor.

We reference Lorraine v. Markel American Insurance Co., 241 F.R.D. 534 (D. Md. 2007), where the court emphasized the necessity of authenticating evidence prior to its admissibility. The court ruled that unauthenticated exhibits could not be considered, underscoring the importance of establishing authenticity before trial.
bob78711new 2025-01-26 01:42 p.m.
This is further supported under federal procedure: Federal Rule of Evidence 901(a) mandates that the proponent of evidence must produce sufficient evidence to support a finding that the item is what it purports to be.
